I"ú<p>An electronic circuit composed of resistotrs and capacitors known as RC circuit [<a href="#ref1">1</a>], whose simplest one with only one resistor $R$ and one capacitor $C$ arranged in series can be used to learn the process of charging [<a href="#ref2">2</a>] and discharging [<a href="#ref3">3</a>] a capacitor.</p>

<h2 id="first-order-circuit">first-order circuit</h2>
<p>The simplest circuit composed of one resistor $R$ and capacitor $C$ is named first-order RC circuit. The circuit can a first-order series RC circuit [<a href="#ref4">4</a>] or a paralel one [<a href="#ref5">5</a>]. Fig. <a href="#fig:rc-circuit-first-order-open">1</a> shows the series and parallel first-order RC circuits.</p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="/assets/img/phys/circuit/rc-circuit-first-order-open.png" alt=".." />
<br />
Figure <a name="fig:rc-circuit-first-order-open">1</a> First order RC circuits arranged in series (left) and parallel (right), both are open.</p>

<p>An switch $S$ is an additional component for controlling when the current flows from battery $\epsilon$ through resistor $R$ and capacitor $C$. The unit for $R$ is $\rm \Omega$ (ohm), for $\epsilon$ is $\rm V$ (volt), and for $C$ is $\rm F$ (farad).</p>

<h2 id="series-circuit">Series circuit</h2>
<p>Using series RC circuit in Fig. <a href="#fig:rc-circuit-first-order-open">1</a> (left) we can charge and discharge a capacitor.</p>

<h3 id="charging-a-capacitor">Charging a capacitor</h3>
<p>At time $t &lt; 0$ it is assumed that the capacitor $C$ does not have any charge $q$ in it. Charging process starts at time $t = 0$ when the switch $S$ is close for the first time and current $I$ begins to flow from the battery $\epsilon$ and pass through the resistor $R$ and capacitor $C$. There will be sudden high value of $I$ and then it is decreasing to zero.</p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="/assets/img/phys/circuit/rc-series-charging.png" alt=".." />
<br />
Figure <a name="fig:rc-series-charging">2</a> Charging a capacitor: $t &lt; 0$ (left) and $t = 0$ (right).</p>

<h3 id="discharging-a-capacitor">Discharging a capacitor</h3>
<p>..</p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="/assets/img/phys/circuit/rc-series-discharging.png" alt=".." />
<br />
Figure <a name="fig:rc-series-charging">3</a> Discharging a capacitor: $t &lt; 0$ (left) and $t = 0$ (right).</p>

